     Cell adhesion and migration are essential in morphogenetic processes and contribute to many diseases


       31


     . Visualizing cytoskeletal dynamics at high resolution during the adhesion/migration process is critical for elucidating the underlying mechanism. However, due to severe photosensitivity, the whole processes of cell adhesion and migration are typically recorded at low framerates, i.e., several seconds per frame, and low light intensities


       9

      ,

       32


     . Under these imaging conditions, either RL deconvolution or temporal continuity-based self-supervised learning


       33


     (Methods) fails to recover and sharpen the intricate structure of F-actin and myosin-II (Fig.

      2a

     , Supplementary Fig.

      12

     , and Supplementary Video

      1

     ). In contrast, the ZS-DeconvNet model effectively improves both the SNR and resolution of the two-color time-lapse recordings of cell


